  "Main_Event": "Tropical Storm/Cyclone",
  "Main_Event_Assessment_With_Annotation": "Severe Tropical Storm Ampil, known in the Philippines as Severe Tropical Storm Inday, was a tropical cyclone that caused moderate damage in the Ryukyu Islands and East and Northeast China in late July 2018."
}

{
  "Perils": "Wind|Rainfall|Flood|Landfall",
  "Perils_Assessment_With_Annotation": {
    "Wind": "Ampil produced gusty winds across the Ryukyu Islands from July 20 to 21, causing disruptions to transport and businesses. Kitadaitōjima recorded wind gusts of 113 km/h (70 mph). Strong winds occurred in the Zhoushan area, with a gust to 33.1 m/s (119 km/h; 74 mph) recorded in Jigu Jiao and a gust to 28.0 m/s (101 km/h; 63 mph) recorded in Xiaoyangshan.",
    "Rainfall": "Ampil generated heavy rains across much of East and Northeast China from July 22 to 25, affecting more than 2.3 million people and causing record-breaking flooding within the watershed of the Songhua River. Rainfall totals exceeded 200 mm (7.9 in) in several areas, with a peak accumulation of 324 mm (12.8 in) recorded in Qinglong County.",
    "Flood": "Ampil generated heavy rains across much of East and Northeast China from July 22 to 25, affecting more than 2.3 million people and causing record-breaking flooding within the watershed of the Songhua River. Flooding along the Hulan River reached an all-time high; the Chaohe River recorded its largest floods since 1998.",
    "Landfall": "Ampil made landfall over eastern Chongming Island in Shanghai, becoming only the third tropical cyclone to make landfall in Shanghai since 1949."
  }
}

